  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Assessing Skill Sets**\n\nI\'m currently evaluating my skill set to see how it aligns with building the \"EMBER Youth Portal\" app. `firebase-integration` seems promising, specifically the Firestore and Auth capabilities. I\'m focusing on how these tools fit with the mobile web app design and its \"modern framework\" requirement.\n\n\n**Defining App Functionality**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the app\'s core functionality, outlining specific screens and features: a home screen with quick actions and announcements, a content submission screen for devotionals and testimonies, a digital check-in screen, and a profile screen with user stats and settings. I see the potential for persistent data storage to track submissions, check-ins, and user profiles. The design is now \"polished\" and is not likely to require simplification.\n\n\n**Revising Scope Expectations**\n\nOkay, there\'s a serious misunderstanding I need to address. The \"single-view\" directive contradicts the multiple screen mockups provided! The design necessitates a full multi-screen mobile app with navigation. I\'m reassessing the initial structural constraint, and I think that, based on the user\'s intent, the single view should be a constraint of the *request*, not the *design* itself. My focus is now on delivering a fully interactive app with home, post submission, check-in, and profile screens, as described.\n\n\n**Reviewing File Structure**\n\nNow, I\'m analyzing the file structure, starting with `metadata.json` to configure the app\'s name and description. I\'ve chosen a literal name, \"EMBER Youth Portal.\" Before proceeding, I\'m doing a skill assessment to determine if `firebase-integration` is necessary. I\'m weighing its benefits for secure, cloud-hosted storage versus the possibility of a client-side solution or a responsive local-state-driven approach.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 4
      nanos: 914141419
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
