  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Constructing App.tsx**\n\nI\'m now diving into the construction of `App.tsx`, focusing on the core navigation and page structure. Currently, my thought process revolves around the bottom navigation bar, which will manage the routing between various pages. I\'m considering a home page, a page for user content, and other sections. Each page will be thoughtfully designed, and all are currently being sketched out. I\'m focusing on the first, the home page, specifically.\n\n\n**Designing Home Page Elements**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the home page\'s specific components. I\'ve designed the profile tab\'s on-click action. I\'m focusing on the \"Welcome\" banner, and considering quick action buttons: \"Devotional,\" \"Testimony,\" and \"Request Prayer\". My thoughts have expanded to the announcement card, and the details and user experience associated with it. I\'m now exploring the implementation of the \"Upcoming Events\" section, with a special card for \"Ignite Youth Camp 2026,\" including registration elements.\n\n\n**Implementing Event Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating event functionality for Aaron. Registration is key, allowing Aaron to confirm details, select options, and submit. Registered events dynamically update his \"Points\" and stats in local storage, providing a \"Registered\" ticket. I\'ve designed a Bento-style Stats Grid showcasing check-ins (dynamic count) and Points. The Events section will list all community events with dates, times, locations, and interactive registration status. Check-in features a profile avatar with an \"ACTIVE\" badge, username, and a pulsing QR code.\n\n\n**Developing Check-In System**\n\nI\'m now building out the check-in functionality for Aaron\'s profile. I\'m focusing on the scan simulation with an Ember flame logo and the level and streak chips. I\'m integrating the pulsing \"SECURE DYNAMIC CODE ACTIVE\" indicator for a visually engaging experience. This will increase Aaron\'s points and stats in local storage after a scan, providing satisfying feedback. I\'m aiming for interactive responsiveness!\n\n\n**Designing Prayer Wall**\n\nI\'m now designing the \"Prayer Wall,\" considering \"Ember Prayers\" as a title. I envision a beautiful interface where users share prayer requests, with a clickable \"Pray\" button for each request. The interaction will be real-time, displaying incrementing counts with a warm ember sparkle animation. There will also be a form to submit new prayer requests. I\'m imagining how the sparks would feel, as well.\n\n**Updating Profile Design**\n\nI\'m now crafting Aaron\'s profile view, starting with a header featuring the profile title, active ring, avatar, and level indicator. The profile will include a Bento-style stats grid displaying reactive data like Points, Check-ins, Prayers Shared, and Posts, reflecting Aaron\'s in-app actions. I\'m also implementing an account and content list with options for profile editing, viewing contributions, adjusting notification settings, privacy settings, support, and a logout button that takes Aaron to a native-feeling lock/sign-in screen.\n\n\n**Verifying Image URLs**\n\nI\'m now cross-referencing the use of hotlinked images. I\'ve compiled a list of URLs from the HTML: a user profile picture, an image for \"Ignite Youth Camp 2026,\" and a check-in image, verifying their locations for integration. I\'m ensuring proper usage for image elements.\n\n\n**Defining App State**\n\nI\'m now defining the initial state for `App.tsx`, focusing on data persistence via `localStorage`. The structure will be clean TypeScript, ensuring a robust and reliable application state. The current plan is to represent core data elements for a great user experience.\n\n\n**Implementing User Data**\n\nI\'m now integrating Aaron\'s profile data, including his name, avatar, level, and stats, with data persistence through `localStorage`. I\'m carefully constructing the app state to represent core user information, as well as a list of `posts`, `prayers`, and `events`, ensuring data is reliable. I also plan to add the Lucide icons to my app.\n\n```\nExisting Summary (empty if none exists yet):\n\n**Constructing App.tsx**\n\nI\'m now diving into the construction of `App.tsx`, focusing on the core navigation and page structure. Currently, my thought process revolves around the bottom navigation bar, which will manage the routing between various pages. I\'m considering a home page, a page for user content, and other sections. Each page will be thoughtfully designed, and all are currently being sketched out. I\'m focusing on the first, the home page, specifically.\n\n\n**Designing Home Page Elements**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the home page\'s specific components. I\'ve designed the profile tab\'s on-click action. I\'m focusing on the \"Welcome\" banner, and considering quick action buttons: \"Devotional,\" \"Testimony,\" and \"Request Prayer\". My thoughts have expanded to the announcement card, and the details and user experience associated with it. I\'m now exploring the implementation of the \"Upcoming Events\" section, with a special card for \"Ignite Youth Camp 2026,\" including registration elements.\n\n\n**Implementing Event Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating event functionality for Aaron. Registration is key, allowing Aaron to confirm details, select options, and submit. Registered events dynamically update his \"Points\" and stats in local storage, providing a \"Registered\" ticket. I\'ve designed a Bento-style Stats Grid showcasing check-ins (dynamic count) and Points. The Events section will list all community events with dates, times, locations, and interactive registration status. Check-in features a profile avatar with an \"ACTIVE\" badge, username, and a pulsing QR code.\n\n\n**Developing Check-In System**\n\nI\'m now building out the check-in functionality for Aaron\'s profile. I\'m focusing on the scan simulation with an Ember flame logo and the level and streak chips. I\'m integrating the pulsing \"SECURE DYNAMIC CODE ACTIVE\" indicator for a visually engaging experience. This will increase Aaron\'s points and stats in local storage after a scan, providing satisfying feedback. I\'m aiming for interactive responsiveness!\n\n\n**Designing Prayer Wall**\n\nI\'m now designing the \"Prayer Wall,\" considering \"Ember Prayers\" as a title. I envision a beautiful interface where users share prayer requests, with a clickable \"Pray\" button for each request. The interaction will be real-time, displaying incrementing counts with a warm ember sparkle animation. There will also be a form to submit new prayer requests. I\'m imagining how the sparks would feel, as well.\n\n**Updating Profile Design**\n\nI\'m now crafting Aaron\'s profile view, starting with a header featuring the profile title, active ring, avatar, and level indicator. The profile will include a Bento-style stats grid displaying reactive data like Points, Check-ins, Prayers Shared, and Posts, reflecting Aaron\'s in-app actions. I\'m also implementing an account and content list with options for profile editing, viewing contributions, adjusting notification settings, privacy settings, support, and a logout button that takes Aaron to a native-feeling lock/sign-in screen.\n\n\n**Verifying Image URLs**\n\nI\'m now cross-referencing the use of hotlinked images. I\'ve compiled a list of URLs from the HTML: a user profile picture, an image for \"Ignite Youth Camp 2026,\" and a check-in image, verifying their locations for integration. I\'m ensuring proper usage for image elements.\n\n\n**Defining App State**\n\nI\'m now defining the initial state for `App.tsx`, focusing on data persistence via `localStorage`. The structure will be clean TypeScript, ensuring a robust and reliable application state. The current plan is to represent core data elements for a great user experience.\n```\n\n\n**Validating Lucide Imports**\n\nI\'m verifying the validity of `lucide-react` icon imports like `Settings`, `Send`, `CheckCircle2`, etc., confirming their availability for a polished UI. I\'ve also re-read the `/src/App.tsx` file to prepare its full implementation. I\'m prioritizing interactive elements, considering features like a notifications drawer, \"Add Prayer\" dialog, and seamless tab transitions based on quick action clicks. I\'m focusing on dynamic updates to points and check-ins.\n\n\n**Implementing Post Submission**\n\nI\'m now integrating the post submission process. I\'m focusing on user input validation and state management, transitioning from a \"Processing\" state to \"Sent for Review\" after submission. I will also be ensuring that contributions are added to \"My Contributions\" and that I increment Aaron\'s post count. I\'m also planning to incorporate a visual pulse effect.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now write a comprehensive, highly polished, and fully interactive React application in `/src/App.tsx`. It implements all the requested screens (Home, Posts, Check-In, Profile) as well as the transition screens (Events, Prayers, Login/Logout, Registration Modals, Edit Profile, and scan simulators) using Tailwind CSS and Lucide React icons, and binds them to a fully functioning local-state and `localStorage` persistence layer. This ensures that the user\'s progress, points, registrations, check-ins, and submissions remain fully dynamic and persistent."
